Sure! Here are some usage examples based on the TypeScript definitions provided for the Firebase Functions module:

### Example 1: Initialize Firebase Functions and Connect to Emulator

```typescript
import { initializeApp } from '@firebase/app';
import { getFunctions, connectFunctionsEmulator } from '@firebase/functions';

// Initialize Firebase app
const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "your-api-key",
  authDomain: "your-auth-domain",
  projectId: "your-project-id",
  storageBucket: "your-storage-bucket",
  messagingSenderId: "your-messaging-sender-id",
  appId: "your-app-id"
};

const app = initializeApp(firebaseConfig);

// Get Functions instance
const functions = getFunctions(app);

// Connect to the emulator
connectFunctionsEmulator(functions, 'localhost', 5001);
```

### Example 2: Call a Cloud Function

```typescript
import { getFunctions, httpsCallable } from '@firebase/functions';

// Initialize Firebase app (assuming app is already initialized)
const functions = getFunctions();

// Get a reference to the callable function
const addMessage = httpsCallable<{ text: string }, { result: string }>(functions, 'addMessage');

// Call the function
addMessage({ text: 'Hello, World! ' })
  .then((result) => {
    console.log('Function result:', result.data);
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error calling function:', error);
  });
```

### Example 3: Handle Function Errors

```typescript
import { getFunctions, httpsCallable, FunctionsError } from '@firebase/functions';

// Initialize Firebase app (assuming app is already initialized)
const functions = getFunctions();

// Get a reference to the callable function
const addMessage = httpsCallable<{ text: string }, { result: string }>(functions, 'addMessage');

// Call the function
addMessage({ text: 'Hello, World! ' })
  .then((result) => {
    console.log('Function result:', result.data);
  })
  .catch((error: FunctionsError) => {
    console.error('Error code:', error.code);
    console.error('Error message:', error.message);
    console.error('Error details:', error.details);
  });
```

### Example 4: Use Custom Domain for Cloud Functions

```typescript
import { initializeApp } from '@firebase/app';
import { getFunctions } from '@firebase/functions';

// Initialize Firebase app
const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "your-api-key",
  authDomain: "your-auth-domain",
  projectId: "your-project-id",
  storageBucket: "your-storage-bucket",
  messagingSenderId: "your-messaging-sender-id",
  appId: "your-app-id"
};

const app = initializeApp(firebaseConfig);

// Get Functions instance with custom domain
const functions = getFunctions(app, 'https://mydomain.com');

// Now you can use the functions instance to call your functions
```

### Example 5: Set Timeout for Callable Function

```typescript
import { getFunctions, httpsCallable } from '@firebase/functions';

// Initialize Firebase app (assuming app is already initialized)
const functions = getFunctions();

// Get a reference to the callable function with custom options
const addMessage = httpsCallable<{ text: string }, { result: string }>(functions, 'addMessage', {
  timeout: 10000 // Set timeout to 10 seconds
});

// Call the function
addMessage({ text: 'Hello, World! ' })
  .then((result) => {
    console.log('Function result:', result.data);
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error calling function:', error);
  });
```

These examples cover initializing Firebase Functions, connecting to the emulator, calling a Cloud Function, handling errors, using a custom domain, and setting a timeout for a callable function.

