Certainly! Below are some usage examples for Firebase in TypeScript. These examples will cover initializing Firebase, using Firestore, Authentication, and Cloud Functions. ### 1. Initializing Firebase

First, you need to initialize Firebase in your project. Make sure you have your Firebase configuration object ready. ```ts
import firebase from 'firebase/app';
import 'firebase/auth';
import 'firebase/firestore';
import 'firebase/functions';

// Your web app's Firebase configuration
const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
  authDomain: "YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN",
  projectId: "YOUR_PROJECT_ID",
  storageBucket: "YOUR_STORAGE_BUCKET",
  messagingSenderId: "YOUR_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID",
  appId: "YOUR_APP_ID"
};

// Initialize Firebase
if (!firebase.apps.length) {
  firebase.initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
} else {
  firebase.app(); // if already initialized, use that one
}
```

### 2. Using Firestore

#### Adding Data to Firestore

```ts
const db = firebase.firestore();

const addUser = async (userId: string, name: string, email: string) => {
  try {
    await db.collection('users').doc(userId).set({
      name,
      email
    });
    console.log('User added successfully');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error adding user: ', error);
  }
};
```

#### Reading Data from Firestore

```ts
const getUser = async (userId: string) => {
  try {
    const userDoc = await db.collection('users').doc(userId).get();
    if (userDoc.exists) {
      console.log('User data:', userDoc.data());
    } else {
      console.log('No such user!');
    }
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error getting user: ', error);
  }
};
```

### 3. Using Authentication

#### Sign Up with Email and Password

```ts
const signUp = async (email: string, password: string) => {
  try {
    const userCredential = await firebase.auth().createUserWithEmailAndPassword(email, password);
    console.log('User signed up:', userCredential.user);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error signing up: ', error);
  }
};
```

#### Sign In with Email and Password

```ts
const signIn = async (email: string, password: string) => {
  try {
    const userCredential = await firebase.auth().signInWithEmailAndPassword(email, password);
    console.log('User signed in:', userCredential.user);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error signing in: ', error);
  }
};
```

### 4. Using Cloud Functions

#### Calling a Cloud Function

```ts
const callFunction = async (functionName: string, data: any) => {
  const functions = firebase.functions();
  const myFunction = functions.httpsCallable(functionName);

  try {
    const result = await myFunction(data);
    console.log('Function result:', result.data);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error calling function: ', error);
  }
};

// Example usage
callFunction('myCloudFunction', { key: 'value' });
```

These examples should help you get started with Firebase in a TypeScript environment. Make sure to replace placeholders like `YOUR_API_KEY`, `YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN`, etc., with your actual Firebase project configuration values.

