Certainly! The TypeScript definitions you provided indicate that the module re-exports everything from the `@firebase/auth/web-extension` package. This package is likely related to Firebase Authentication for web extensions. Below are some usage examples demonstrating how you might use Firebase Authentication in a web extension context. These examples assume you have already set up Firebase in your project. ### Example 1: Initializing Firebase in a Web Extension

First, you need to initialize Firebase in your web extension's background script or content script. ```typescript
import { initializeApp } from 'firebase/app';
import { getAuth } from '@firebase/auth/web-extension';

// Your web app's Firebase configuration
const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
  authDomain: "YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN",
  projectId: "YOUR_PROJECT_ID",
  storageBucket: "YOUR_STORAGE_BUCKET",
  messagingSenderId: "YOUR_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID",
  appId: "YOUR_APP_ID"
};

// Initialize Firebase
const app = initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
const auth = getAuth(app);
```

### Example 2: Signing in a User

You can sign in a user using email and password. ```typescript
import { signInWithEmailAndPassword } from '@firebase/auth/web-extension';

const email = "user@example.com";
const password = "user_password";

signInWithEmailAndPassword(auth, email, password)
  .then((userCredential) => {
    // Signed in
    const user = userCredential.user;
    console.log('User signed in:', user);
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error signing in:', error);
  });
```

### Example 3: Signing out a User

To sign out a user, you can use the `signOut` function. ```typescript
import { signOut } from '@firebase/auth/web-extension';

signOut(auth)
  .then(() => {
    console.log('User signed out');
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error signing out:', error);
  });
```

### Example 4: Listening for Authentication State Changes

You can listen for authentication state changes to react to user sign-in or sign-out events. ```typescript
import { onAuthStateChanged } from '@firebase/auth/web-extension';

onAuthStateChanged(auth, (user) => {
  if (user) {
    // User is signed in
    console.log('User is signed in:', user);
  } else {
    // User is signed out
    console.log('User is signed out');
  }
});
```

### Example 5: Creating a New User

To create a new user with email and password, you can use the `createUserWithEmailAndPassword` function. ```typescript
import { createUserWithEmailAndPassword } from '@firebase/auth/web-extension';

const newUserEmail = "newuser@example.com";
const newUserPassword = "new_user_password";

createUserWithEmailAndPassword(auth, newUserEmail, newUserPassword)
  .then((userCredential) => {
    // User created
    const user = userCredential.user;
    console.log('New user created:', user);
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.error('Error creating new user:', error);
  });
```

These examples should help you get started with Firebase Authentication in a web extension context. Make sure to replace placeholder values like `YOUR_API_KEY` with your actual Firebase project configuration values.

