Certainly! Based on the TypeScript definitions you provided, it looks like the `firebase` dependency is re-exporting everything from the `@firebase/auth/cordova` module. Below are some usage examples that demonstrate how you might use Firebase Authentication in a TypeScript project, specifically targeting a Cordova environment. ### Example 1: Initializing Firebase in a Cordova App

First, you need to initialize Firebase in your Cordova app. Make sure you have your Firebase configuration object ready. ```typescript
import { initializeApp } from 'firebase/app';
import { getAuth } from '@firebase/auth/cordova';

// Your web app's Firebase configuration
const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
  authDomain: "YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN",
  projectId: "YOUR_PROJECT_ID",
  storageBucket: "YOUR_STORAGE_BUCKET",
  messagingSenderId: "YOUR_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID",
  appId: "YOUR_APP_ID"
};

// Initialize Firebase
const app = initializeApp(firebaseConfig);

// Initialize Firebase Authentication and get a reference to the service
const auth = getAuth(app);
```

### Example 2: User Sign-Up

Here's how you can implement user sign-up using email and password. ```typescript
import { createUserWithEmailAndPassword } from '@firebase/auth/cordova';

const signUp = async (email: string, password: string) => {
  try {
    const userCredential = await createUserWithEmailAndPassword(auth, email, password);
    // Signed in 
    const user = userCredential.user;
    console.log('User signed up:', user);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error signing up:', error);
  }
};

// Usage
signUp('user@example.com', 'password123');
```

### Example 3: User Sign-In

Here's how you can implement user sign-in using email and password. ```typescript
import { signInWithEmailAndPassword } from '@firebase/auth/cordova';

const signIn = async (email: string, password: string) => {
  try {
    const userCredential = await signInWithEmailAndPassword(auth, email, password);
    // Signed in 
    const user = userCredential.user;
    console.log('User signed in:', user);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error signing in:', error);
  }
};

// Usage
signIn('user@example.com', 'password123');
```

### Example 4: User Sign-Out

Here's how you can implement user sign-out. ```typescript
import { signOut } from '@firebase/auth/cordova';

const logOut = async () => {
  try {
    await signOut(auth);
    console.log('User signed out');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error signing out:', error);
  }
};

// Usage
logOut();
```

### Example 5: Listening to Authentication State

You can listen to changes in the authentication state to handle user sign-in and sign-out events. ```typescript
import { onAuthStateChanged } from '@firebase/auth/cordova';

onAuthStateChanged(auth, (user) => {
  if (user) {
    // User is signed in
    console.log('User is signed in:', user);
  } else {
    // User is signed out
    console.log('User is signed out');
  }
});
```

These examples should give you a good starting point for using Firebase Authentication in a Cordova environment with TypeScript. Make sure to replace placeholder values like `YOUR_API_KEY` with your actual Firebase project configuration.

