Certainly! Below are some usage examples of the Firebase library in TypeScript, specifically focusing on Firebase Authentication. The examples assume that you have already set up your Firebase project and have the necessary configuration details. ### Example 1: Initializing Firebase

First, you need to initialize Firebase in your project. This is usually done in a separate file, such as `firebaseConfig.ts`. ```typescript
import firebase from 'firebase/app';
import 'firebase/auth';

const firebaseConfig = {
  apiKey: "YOUR_API_KEY",
  authDomain: "YOUR_AUTH_DOMAIN",
  projectId: "YOUR_PROJECT_ID",
  storageBucket: "YOUR_STORAGE_BUCKET",
  messagingSenderId: "YOUR_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID",
  appId: "YOUR_APP_ID"
};

// Initialize Firebase
if (!firebase.apps.length) {
  firebase.initializeApp(firebaseConfig);
} else {
  firebase.app(); // if already initialized, use that one
}

export default firebase;
```

### Example 2: User Registration

Here's how you can create a new user using Firebase Authentication. ```typescript
import firebase from './firebaseConfig';

const registerUser = async (email: string, password: string) => {
  try {
    const userCredential = await firebase.auth().createUserWithEmailAndPassword(email, password);
    console.log('User registered:', userCredential.user);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error registering user:', error);
  }
};

// Usage
registerUser('test@example.com', 'password123');
```

### Example 3: User Login

Here's how you can log in an existing user. ```typescript
import firebase from './firebaseConfig';

const loginUser = async (email: string, password: string) => {
  try {
    const userCredential = await firebase.auth().signInWithEmailAndPassword(email, password);
    console.log('User logged in:', userCredential.user);
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error logging in user:', error);
  }
};

// Usage
loginUser('test@example.com', 'password123');
```

### Example 4: User Logout

Here's how you can log out a user. ```typescript
import firebase from './firebaseConfig';

const logoutUser = async () => {
  try {
    await firebase.auth().signOut();
    console.log('User logged out');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error logging out user:', error);
  }
};

// Usage
logoutUser();
```

### Example 5: Observing Auth State

You can observe the authentication state to react to changes, such as when a user logs in or out. ```typescript
import firebase from './firebaseConfig';

firebase.auth().onAuthStateChanged(user => {
  if (user) {
    console.log('User is signed in:', user);
  } else {
    console.log('No user is signed in');
  }
});
```

### Example 6: Password Reset

Here's how you can send a password reset email. ```typescript
import firebase from './firebaseConfig';

const sendPasswordResetEmail = async (email: string) => {
  try {
    await firebase.auth().sendPasswordResetEmail(email);
    console.log('Password reset email sent');
  } catch (error) {
    console.error('Error sending password reset email:', error);
  }
};

// Usage
sendPasswordResetEmail('test@example.com');
```

These examples cover some of the basic functionalities provided by Firebase Authentication. You can expand on these examples to include more advanced features such as social login, email verification, and more.

